      <byline class="print_byline">By GRACE GLUECK</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Glueck, Grace</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Grace Glueck reviews Haitian art at Bruce Museum (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>'Haitian Art From the Collection of Mrs. Robert C. Graham'  Bruce Museum of Arts and Science  1 Museum Drive  Greenwich, Conn.  Through Sept. 3</p>
        <p>A chromaticism ranging from bright to shrill dominates the Bruce Museum's exhibition ''A Cultural Kaleidoscope.'' More than 30 paintings by 20th-century Haitian artists -- among them Wilson Bigaud, Philome Obin and J. B. Bottex -- appear here, dealing with subjects ranging from the religious and the historical to scenes of daily life.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>'Haitian Art From the Collection of Mrs. Robert C. Graham'  Bruce Museum of Arts and Science  1 Museum Drive  Greenwich, Conn.  Through Sept. 3</p>
        <p>A chromaticism ranging from bright to shrill dominates the Bruce Museum's exhibition ''A Cultural Kaleidoscope.'' More than 30 paintings by 20th-century Haitian artists -- among them Wilson Bigaud, Philome Obin and J. B. Bottex -- appear here, dealing with subjects ranging from the religious and the historical to scenes of daily life.</p>
        <p>Among the treats is Bottex's ''Samson and the Lion'' (1966), a Rousseau-like depiction of the long-haired biblical hero attacking a Disneyesque beast in a stylized natural landscape. Take your sunglasses; the color in this show really blasts.</p>
        <p>GRACE GLUECK</p>
        <p>ART IN REVIEW</p>
      </block>
